thanks for the questions! You are one of our loudest supporters, so it's refreshing when critique comes from you, as it keeps us balanced and honest.

Getting perfect sync on the validators' side is a work in progress. When this happens, their opinions of miners differ. It's still ok, but weight copiers start to make more than honest validators. In this case, people allocate even more stake to the validator. I have campaigned for people to move stake in the past and have had pushback that they had a fiduciary responsibility to their delegates to get the highest return.

We have been spread really thin and have mainly focused on the decentralized training components of the subnet. We are in the middle of a big push, but we're already exploring ways of improving validator trust, which we hope will help make other validators more profitable and make a case for stake migrating.

I think we can both agree now that stake concentration has little to do with the subnet being permissionless, but nonetheless, it represents an important attack vector - abuse of power.

Now let's go through this thought experiment: What is the incentive for the Templar team to act maliciously? I might be biased, but it's not game theory optimal, at least not to me. DTAO becomes a high trust game. Not because we intend to stop building trustless products, but because if you mar your integrity, you lose all you have worked for - all of Templar's value disappears in one candle, with stake leaving our validator and value from the subnet.

So no, it's not something we are going to do.

However, it is a valid concern.

In order to prevent this moral hazard from materializing, we don't mine, except Joel, who was a miner - one of the conditions of his employment. I think this is a choice I would make over and over again, as Joel has been such a blessing to the team. We trust Joel 100%, but still don't let him near the validator. Only Evan and I have access to it.

We are also exploring different ways of orchestrating the validators in a way that is more inclusive. Things we are looking at include TEEs (our validator runs the code, other validators attest to it) or maybe a Chutes auditor model.
